Under aerobic conditions, cholesterol can be catalyzed by cholesterol oxidase (ChOx) to produce H2O2. Thus, the B, N-CDs could serve as an indirect sensor for cholesterol detection. As indicated in Fig. 4
                        A–B, the absorbance of the “B, N-CDs + TMB + ChOx” system demonstrated a positive correlation with the concentration of cholesterol (8–250 μM). The absorbance around 652 nm was found to be good linear (A = 0.00401C + 0.2715, R2 = 0.9989) versus concentration cholesterol from 15 to 160 μM (Fig. 4C). The LOD of cholesterol was then estimated to be 0.87 μM, lower than most previous nanomaterials (Table 1
                        ). The sensitivity and selectivity of colorimetric assay of B, N-CDs toward cholesterol was illustrated in Fig. 4D. When other interfering substances including glucose, Na+, K+, Mg2+, ascorbic acid, uric acid, Hcy, Phe, GSH, Val, Gly, Ile and Lys was added, the absorbance did not show any obvious change. Even the concentration of each interfering compound exceeded that of cholesterol by a factor of 15, only cholesterol showed a notable alteration in absorbance, demonstrating the remarkable selectivity of B, N-CDs for cholesterol detection through colorimetric methods. The selectivity range of B, N-CDs for cholesterol was wider or comparable related to that of the reported materials (Table S2).
